5","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Anglie"},"da":{"1360–":"1360–Afdød","1361–Female":"1361–Afdød","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1360–":"1360–Overleden","1361–Female":"1361–Overleden","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1360–":"1360–Deceased","1361–Female":"1361–Deceased","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Pope was born in 1360, in Twyford, Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Robert Pope."},"et":{"1360–":"1360–Surnud","1361–Female":"1361–Surnud","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1360–":"1360–Kuollut","1361–Female":"1361–Kuollut","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1360–":"1360–Décédé","1361–Female":"1361–Décédée","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1455":"1455","1497":"1497","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Twyford, Norfolk, England":"Twyford, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Pope est né en 1360, à Twyford, Norfolk, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Robert Pope."},"de":{"1360–":"1360–Verstorben","1361–Female":"1361–Verstorben","1385–1497":"1385–1497","1360–Male":"1360–Verstorben","1455":"1455","1